<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-343-802  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 343 802.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  April 16 1990 v24 n16 p22(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Satellite communications takes flight; new satellite technologymay soon supply communications links for computers.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Alexander, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>New satellite technology may soon provide communication links forcomputers via satellite antennas, data communications technologiesand services.andP;  The antennas, named phase arrays, are the size ofan open newspaper and only one-fourth inch thick.andP;  The phasearrays can be shaped to the surface contours of an airplane orother vehicle and can be electronically controlled.andP;  Phase arraysfor the airline industry are expensive, running about $140,000,but less expensive, smaller versions are being used for a varietyof ground mobile applications, such as trucking.andP;  Roberts ExpressInc plans to equip 975 trucks with two-way messaging systems basedon a satellite communications system developed by Qualcomm.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Satellite CommunicationsLaptop computersAirline IndustryTrucking IndustryCommunications TechnologyAntennas.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>